cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 85 miles NNE of Grand Cayman
cyclone.trajectory: Moving northeast toward central Cuba tonight, then expected to turn north-northwest and approach the Florida Keys and far-southern Florida Sunday night before bending westward into the eastern Gulf of Mexico early next week.
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: central Cuba (first), then possibly near the Florida Keys/south-Florida coast

weather_observation.watch_coast: Florida coast from north of Jupiter Inlet to the Brevard/Volusia county line
weather_observation.warning_coast: Florida coast from Jupiter Inlet to Bonita Beach including Florida Bay and the Keys
weather_observation.impacted_coast: Southern and central Florida peninsula (including Canaveral area), Florida Keys, north-western Bahamas, and portions of Cuba
weather_observation.wind: Tropical-storm-force winds (sustained 25–35 kt with higher gusts) possible late Sunday night through Monday as the center passes south of the port.
weather_observation.storm_surge: 1–2 ft of surge above ground level possible along the Brevard coast, including Port Canaveral, mainly with onshore winds around high tide.
weather_observation.rainfall: 6–12 inches of rain with locally higher amounts could overspread east-central Florida, leading to flash and urban flooding around the port complex.
weather_observation.other_hazards: Dangerous surf and rip currents along the Space Coast; isolated tornadoes cannot be ruled out in outer bands Sunday night–Monday.
